snippet.textDisplay: I have a feeling that whole channel was created to make that food scientist feel better. Because it's food scientist! Everybody cooking how they want it to taste. Wtf?!?! Yeah, there are two axioms about mixing ingredients and cooking, but come on. Do you, western people, eating pancakes with condensed milk? Or milk soup with rice, buckwheat, or pasta? Chocolate butter? Kefir as drink? Okroshka?(cold half kefir, half milk whey, with boiled potatoes, eggs, milk sausage or ham, fresh pickles, dill, parsley and some mustard.) Last one is perfect for summer.  That's my food, and scientist won't convince me that those are wrong

snippet.textDisplay:
help to understand:
fondant: french offical term for "soft" popatoes. potatoes can be soft or hard, there are many forms, but these two forms are the biggest differences in cooking. some dishes need potatoes, who are better to suck the water/flavour into them, because the sauce isnt thick. sometimes more white and thereby called flour-potatoes. the pommes potatoes are hard, to stay in form, but thick pommes tend to be sooft, to have a nice soft tecture behind the crust.



bordelaise: Bordeaux, a region in france, his citizens are called Bordelais. the strange stuff in the glass is Bone marrow from the cow. really tasty and easily selfmade with actual bones from cows, get the center out, add some muscat and sandwitchs-bread and milk, form balls, put into the soup. the bordelaise souce use the specific taste of bone marrow to intensive the beef smell without wasting beef for the sauce. it is economic and green cooking to recycle the whole animal and use food in the best way for the taste. some cooks would claim, that bone marrow give an better taste then actual beef into the sauce and it could be true. it is definitive easier and cheaper to use.


mushroms, wine and truffles are from the area of bordeaux. the cost of some of these products increase, because they were imported and suffered under Trumps taxes.
